      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey can u help me out? im studying for bio and im kinda stuck on mitosis. can u just give me a step by step of the different stages? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Of course, I can help you with that! Mitosis is a process where a single cell divides into two identical daughter cells. Here are the steps:\n\n1. **Prophase**: The chromosomes condense and become visible. The nuclear envelope breaks down, and the mitotic spindle forms from microtubules.\n\n2. **Prometaphase**: The nuclear envelope is completely broken down. The spindle fibers attach to the kinetochores of the chromosomes.\n\n3. **Metaphase**: The chromosomes align at the metaphase plate, an imaginary line equidistant from the two spindle poles.\n\n4. **Anaphase**: The sister chromatids are pulled apart by the spindle fibers and move toward opposite poles of the cell.\n\n5. **Telophase**: The chromosomes decondense, and nuclear envelopes reform around each set of chromosomes, resulting in two separate nuclei within the cell.\n\n6. **Cytokinesis**: The cell membrane pinches inwards, dividing the cytoplasm and resulting in two daughter cells, each with a complete set of chromosomes.\n\nRemember, these stages are crucial for ensuring that each daughter cell receives an identical set of chromosomes. Good luck with your studies!",
      "source": "target",
